.TH _PRINTF 3 "November 2025" "Holberton School" "Programmer's Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function is a custom implementation of the standard C library printf function.
It produces output according to the
.I format
argument, which is a character string composed of zero or more directives.
.PP
Each conversion specification is introduced by the character
.BR % .
The arguments following the
.I format
argument are converted and printed according to the corresponding conversion
specifier in the format string.
.SS Conversion Specifiers
.TP
.B c
Print the argument as an unsigned char.
.TP
.B s
Print the string pointed to by the argument. If the argument is NULL,
the string "(null)" is printed.
.TP
.B d, i
Print the argument as a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B u
Print the argument as an unsigned decimal integer.
.TP
.B %
Print a literal percent character.
.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful completion,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed to stdout, not including the
terminating null byte used to end output to strings.
.PP
If the
.I format
argument is NULL, the function returns -1.
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
This implementation does not handle buffer management like the standard printf.
.IP \(bu 2
Flag characters, field width, precision, and length modifiers are not supported.
.IP \(bu 2
For unrecognized conversion specifiers, a literal percent sign followed by
the character is printed.
.SH EXAMPLE
.nf
#include "main.h"

int main(void)
{
    int count;

    count = _printf("Hello, %s!\n", "World");
    _printf("Number: %d, Char: %c\n", 42, 'A');
    _printf("Percent: %%\n");
    _printf("Returned: %d characters\n", count);

    return (0);
}
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3)
.SH AUTHOR
Holberton School printf implementation group